<section id="what-is-fengshui">
      <h2>What Is Feng Shui?</h2>
      <p>Feng Shui (<span class="chinese-char">風水</span>, literally "wind-water") is the traditional Chinese system of geomancy &mdash; the art and science of assessing landscapes and dwellings to understand how natural energy (<span class="chinese-char">氣</span>, Qi) flows through them. Its purpose is to identify locations where Qi gathers beneficially and to orient structures so inhabitants live in harmony with natural forces.</p>
      <p>Classical Feng Shui is not interior decorating. It is an ancient and rigorous discipline of land assessment, rooted in millennia of empirical observation, cosmological theory, and scholarly refinement. The <em>Zangshu</em> (<span class="chinese-char">葬書</span>, Book of Burial) states: "Qi rides the wind and scatters, but is retained when encountering water." This single principle gives Feng Shui its name and foundational logic.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="historical-origins">
      <h2>Historical Origins</h2>
      <p>Feng Shui's roots stretch back over 3,500 years. Shang Dynasty (c. 1600-1046 BCE) burial sites show careful orientation according to cardinal directions and terrain, demonstrating that auspicious siting was already practised during China's earliest recorded civilisations.</p>
      <p>The foundational text is the <em>Zangshu</em>, attributed to <strong>Guo Pu (<span class="chinese-char">郭璞</span>)</strong> of the Jin Dynasty (266-420 CE). He systematised burial geomancy principles, articulating how landforms determine Qi flow.</p>
      <p>During the <strong>Tang Dynasty</strong>, master <strong>Yang Yunsong (<span class="chinese-char">楊筠松</span>)</strong> served as imperial geomancer before founding the Form School in Jiangxi. His texts &mdash; the <em>Hanlongjing</em> (<span class="chinese-char">撼龍經</span>) and <em>Yilongjing</em> (<span class="chinese-char">疑龍經</span>) &mdash; laid out precise methods for tracing dragon veins through mountain ranges.</p>
      <p>The <strong>Song Dynasty</strong> saw the Compass School mature, with masters developing Flying Stars (Xuan Kong) and refining the Luopan. Feng Shui became integral to state planning: capitals like <strong>Chang'an</strong> and <strong>Luoyang</strong> were sited according to geomantic principles.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="form-school">
      <h2>The Form School (<span class="chinese-char">巒頭派</span>)</h2>
      <p>The Form School reads the physical landscape directly &mdash; mountains, rivers, terrain contours &mdash; to understand Qi movement. Central is the concept of <strong>mountains as dragons</strong>: ridges along which Qi flows are <strong>dragon veins</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">龍脈</span>). A geomancer traces these from distant peaks to where Qi settles &mdash; the <strong>dragon's lair</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">龍穴</span>).</p>
      <p>Any site is assessed through the <strong>Four Celestial Animals</strong>:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Azure Dragon (<span class="chinese-char">青龍</span>) &mdash; East</strong>: Hills to the left (facing south), slightly higher, representing protective yang energy.</li>
        <li><strong>White Tiger (<span class="chinese-char">白虎</span>) &mdash; West</strong>: Terrain to the right, lower and subdued. If higher than the Dragon, the site is inauspicious.</li>
        <li><strong>Black Tortoise (<span class="chinese-char">玄武</span>) &mdash; North</strong>: Mountain behind, providing solid backing and shielding from northern winds.</li>
        <li><strong>Vermilion Bird (<span class="chinese-char">朱雀</span>) &mdash; South</strong>: Open space in front, allowing Qi to gather in a "bright hall" (<span class="chinese-char">明堂</span>).</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="compass-school">
      <h2>The Compass School (<span class="chinese-char">理氣派</span>)</h2>
      <p>The Compass School introduces mathematical precision using the <strong>Luopan</strong> compass. It maps invisible energies of compass directions, trigram sectors, and temporal cycles.</p>
      <p>The <strong>Eight Trigrams</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">八卦</span>) form the backbone of directional analysis. Derived from the Yijing, the trigrams &mdash; Qian, Kun, Zhen, Xun, Kan, Li, Gen, Dui &mdash; each govern a direction with specific elemental and symbolic associations.</p>
      <p>The most sophisticated method is <strong>Xuan Kong Feixing</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">玄空飛星</span>, Flying Stars), which assigns shifting numerical values to directional sectors according to 20-year, annual, and monthly cycles. This allows practitioners to assess when a site's energies peak and decline.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="luopan">
      <h2>The Luopan Compass</h2>
      <p>The Luopan (<span class="chinese-char">羅盤</span>) is a portable encyclopaedia of Chinese cosmology. At its centre lies the <strong>Heaven Pool</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">天池</span>) &mdash; a magnetic needle pointing to magnetic south. Radiating outward are concentric rings containing:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>24 Mountains (<span class="chinese-char">二十四山</span>)</strong> &mdash; 24 sectors of 15 degrees each, combining Earthly Branches, Heavenly Stems, and trigrams.</li>
        <li><strong>Trigram rings</strong> &mdash; Earlier Heaven and Later Heaven arrangements for different analytical purposes.</li>
        <li><strong>Stems and Branches</strong> &mdash; Various combinations for temporal and directional calculations.</li>
        <li><strong>28 Lunar Mansions</strong> &mdash; Correlating terrestrial directions with celestial constellations.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="imperial">
      <h2>Feng Shui in Imperial China</h2>
      <p>The <strong>Forbidden City</strong> sits on a north-south axis with Jingshan Hill behind (Black Tortoise), Tiananmen Square to the south (bright hall), and the Golden Water River curving before the entrance in a jade-belt formation.</p>
      <p>The <strong>Ming Tombs</strong> valley was selected for near-perfect geomantic configuration: a horseshoe of mountains on three sides with a watercourse flowing through the southern opening. Thirteen Ming emperors rest within this single embrace.</p>
      <p><strong>Chang'an</strong> was positioned on the Wei River plain backed by the Qinling Mountains; <strong>Luoyang</strong> sat at the confluence of the Luo and Yi rivers. These were systematic geomantic selections at the highest imperial level.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="five-elements">
      <h2>Five Elements in Feng Shui</h2>
      <p>The <a href="/wuxing/">Five Elements</a> provide the language for describing how Qi manifests. In the Form School, landscape shapes encode elements: pointed peaks are Fire, flat tops are Earth, rounded hills Metal, undulations Water, tall formations Wood.</p>
      <p>In the Compass School, each trigram sector carries an element: Kan (north) is Water, Li (south) Fire, Zhen/Xun are Wood, Qian/Dui are Metal, Gen/Kun are Earth. The interaction between a building's direction and these sectors determines energy quality.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="classical-vs-modern">
      <h2>Classical vs. Modern Feng Shui</h2>
      <p><strong>Classical Feng Shui</strong> (pre-Qing) requires years of training: physical site assessment, Luopan readings, Flying Star calculations, 24 mountains analysis, and dragon vein tracing. Practitioners were literate scholars integrating cosmology, astronomy, and geography.</p>
      <p><strong>Modern pop Feng Shui</strong> strips these foundations, reducing the discipline to generic rules divorced from compass measurement or landscape assessment. The Black Sect Tantric Buddhist (BTB) method &mdash; a modern invention with no classical Chinese lineage &mdash; is often confused with traditional geomancy.</p>
      <p>The pre-Qing classical texts &mdash; from Guo Pu through Yang Yunsong to Song and Ming masters &mdash; represent a coherent, philosophically grounded body of knowledge. Serious Feng Shui study begins with these sources.</p>
    </section>
